
- User‑friendly drag‑and‑drop interface  
- Supports wide range of data sources  
- High design flexibility for custom visuals  
- Large, active user community  
- Downside: pricing model

- Joining = same data source, creates flattened table  
- Blending = different data sources, queries remain separate, per‑worksheet behavior

- Live connection = real‑time queries, slower on large data  
- Extract = optimized static snapshot, faster, supports refresh schedules

- Dimension = categorical descriptor  
- Measure = numeric, aggregatable value

- Discrete (blue) = countable, categorical  
- Continuous (green) = numeric range

- Dashboard best practices: design for audience, remove clutter, use color intentionally, choose correct chart type, ensure smooth user flow

- Order of operations: filters follow Tableau’s pipeline; use context filters to control precedence

- Parameters = user‑defined dynamic inputs  
- Sets = logical grouping based on conditions  
- Groups = manual grouping of values

- Calculated fields = custom fields created from existing fields
- CASE VS IF -- CASE requires less repetitive fields calling 

- Dual axis = overlay two measures on one chart

- LOD expressions:  
  - FIXED = ignore view granularity  
  - INCLUDE = add dimensions - when there is hierarchy for example
  - EXCLUDE = remove dimensions

- Actions: filter, highlight, go to URL, go to sheet, change parameter, change set values

- Data security: user‑level, row‑level, column‑level

- Performance tips: optimize data sources, simplify workbook, reduce complex calcs, use extracts, use filters, incremental refresh

- ATTR() displays * when multiple values exist

